  "texts": [
    "In particular, context enrichment techniques based on program analysis and post-generation repair techniques centered on feedback loops have become the standard for improving the quality of LLM-generated tests.",
    "More advanced work has begun to build autonomous testing agents and hybrid systems that deeply integrate with traditional tools.",
    "However, key gaps persist.",
    "While test usability has improved (i.e., ensuring tests are compilable and executable), improving test effectiveness (i.e., their ability to detect real faults) remains a major challenge.",
    "Furthermore, the lack of standardized evaluation benchmarks, an insufficient understanding of the models' intrinsic limitations, and the gap between academic research and industrial practice are three major obstacles hindering further progress.To structure our analysis, we address the following research questions (RQs):• RQ1: How are the core strategies for using LLMs (pre-training, fine-tuning, and prompt engineering) applied, and how have they evolved in the context of unit test generation?• RQ2: Which classic software engineering techniques are used to enhance LLM-based unit test generation, and how do they combine to form a systematic approach to managing the generation process?"
  ],
